source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-3048
Reason: The molecule in question, [(1E,3Z)-1,2,3,4-tetrabromo-4-phenylbuta-1,3-dien-1-yl]benzene, can be analyzed by comparing it with benzene and examining the effects of added functional groups. Benzene has a melting point of 5.5°C. Introducing a phenyl group generally raises the melting point due to increased molecular weight and enhanced pi-pi stacking interactions; this effect could increase the melting point by roughly 20°C. Each bromine atom, due to its high atomic mass and contributions to the van der Waals forces, could raise the melting point. A single bromine might increase the melting point by approximately 15°C. Given that there are four bromine atoms, this would suggest a total increase of around 60°C for the four bromines. However, the presence of the double bonds in the butadiene moiety introduces rigidity to the molecule, which could further increase the melting point, possibly contributing an additional 20°C. These effects are cumulative. Therefore, starting with the base melting point of benzene and adding the effects of the functional groups give us a predicted value.
Prediction: 5.5 (benzene base) + 20 (phenyl group) + 60 (four bromine atoms) + 20 (double bonds rigidity) = approximately 105.5°C
